    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>The Michigan Abortion Referendum Committee (MARC) was organized in 1972 to coordinate the campaign for a "Yes" vote on Proposition B, abortion reform, in the November 1972 election.</p>
      <p>The fore-runner of MARC was the Michigan Coordinating Committee for Abortion Law Reform (MCCARL), which sought to gain approval of the Michigan legislature for the liberalization of the state's abortion laws from 1969-1971. In June, 1971, when the proposed legislation became stalled in committee, MCCARL), which sought to gain approval of the Michigan legislature for the liberalization of the state's abortion laws from 1969-1971. In June, 1971, when the proposed legislation became stalled in committee, MCCARL launched a petition drive to submit the abortion issue to a popular referendum at the November, 1972, general election. The proposal provided for "a licensed medical or osteopathic physician to perform an abortion at the request of the patient, if (1) the period of gestation has not exceeded 20 weeks, and (2) the procedure is performed in a licensed hospital or other facility approved by the Department of Public Health." Following a vigorous campaign, Proposition B was defeated by a 2-1 margin.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The papers of MARC have been organized both chronologically and by type of material. Papers from the drive for legislation (1969-1971) are followed by materials from the petition drive (1971-1972) and the referendum campaign (1972). Campaign materials include the publicity and press releases of MARC, organizing materials, publicity distributed by the group opposed to Proposition B, the Michigan Right to Life Committee, and correspondence.</p>
    </scopecontent>
